The paper deals with the problem of polynomial learnability of probability distributions, particularly Gaussian mixture distributions, which is a topic of interest in machine learning and theoretical computer science. The use of tools from real algebraic geometry suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. The focus on learning algorithms and dimensionality reduction techniques suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-categories. The analysis of polynomial families of distributions suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. Finally, the use of statistical methods and probability theory suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category.
